{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991190084,"exec_count":87,"id":"547bca","input":"clean_state_acts <- state_acts %>%\n    dplyr::select(State, Title, Text, Enacted.Date, Type, Repealed.Date) %>% #what variables do I want - #too many packages with the same functions\n    filter(Type == \"Laws and Regulations\") %>% #only want Laws and Regulations\n    filter(Enacted.Date != \"\") %>% \n\n    #want Enacted Year only\n    mutate(Enacted.Date = ymd_hms(Enacted.Date)) %>% #date includes time and a timezone - use ymd_hms()\n    mutate(Enacted.Year = year(Enacted.Date)) %>%\n\n    #sort by year and then state\n    dplyr::select(Enacted.Year, State, Title, Text) %>% #too many packages with the same functions\n    arrange(Enacted.Year, State) %>%\n\n    #separate out US (all states) and DC data\n    filter(State != \"US\" & State != \"DC\")\n\nhead(clean_state_acts)","kernel":"ir","last":192,"output":{"0":{"data":{"iframe":"fba18b5a0bef1c5a4679075992e678bab6d1a395","text/latex":"A data.frame: 6 × 4\n\\begin{tabular}{r|llll}\n  & Enacted.Year & State & Title & Text\\\\\n  & <dbl> & <chr> & <chr> & <chr>\\\\\n\\hline\n\t1 & 1996 & MA & State Agency Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirement & State fleets must acquire AFVs according to the requirements of the\nEnergy Policy Act (EPAct) of 1992 and the Massachusetts Office of\nVehicle Management (OVM) must approve any light-duty vehicle\nacquisition. All agencies must purchase the most economical,\nfuel-efficient, and low emission vehicles appropriate to their mission.\nOVM, in collaboration with the Massachusetts Department of Energy\nResources, will set new minimum standards for vehicle mileage and work\nwith agencies to acquire vehicles that provide the best value for the\nCommonwealth on a total cost of ownership basis. (Reference Executive\nOrder 388, 1996, and Massachusetts Executive Office of Administration\nand Finance Administrative Bulletin 10, 2010)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   \\\\\n\t2 & 2000 & IA & State Fleet Biofuels Use and Fuel Efficiency                        & As part of the Green Government Initiative, the Iowa Office of Energy\nIndependence (OEI), Department of Administrative Services, Department of\nNatural Resources, and Department of Transportation lead a Biofuels Task\nForce. This group focuses on issues including increasing each state\nagency's use of biofuels to the maximum amount feasible and increasing\nthe fuel efficiency of the state's vehicle fleet. The Biofuels Task\nForce sets specific five- and ten-year targets related to these areas,\nwhich are included in the Green Government Master Plan. Progress toward\nthese goals will be tracked using a reporting system developed under the\nGreen Government Initiative, and resulting data will be made public via\nthe OEI whenever possible. (Reference Executive Order 6, 2008)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              \\\\\n\t3 & 2001 & MD & Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirements             & Maryland established an AFV goal under the plan for \\textbackslash{}'Sustaining\nMaryland\\textbackslash{}'s Future with Clean Power, Green Buildings and Energy\nEfficiency.\\textbackslash{}' The state will revise fleet policy and purchasing\nguidelines to offer more flexibility in purchasing, where practical, low\nemission vehicles and AFVs for its fleet. The state must ensure that an\naverage of 50\\% of the fuel used to operate bi-fuel and flexible fuel\nvehicles are alternative fuel. The state must also help develop the\nrefueling and maintenance infrastructure required to make using certain\ntypes of AFV use practical. The state may provide technical assistance\nand other incentives to use clean technology, where practical, in state\ntransit fleets. (Reference {[}Executive\nOrder{]}(https://governor.maryland.gov/category/executive-orders/)\n01.01.2001.02)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       \\\\\n\t4 & 2001 & NY & Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirements             & All new light-duty vehicles that state agencies and other affected\nentities procure must be AFVs, with the exception of designated\nspecialty, police, or emergency vehicles. Hybrid electric vehicles\nqualify under these requirements. State agencies and other affected\nentities that operate medium- and heavy-duty vehicles must implement\nstrategies to reduce petroleum consumption and emissions by using\nalternative fuels and improving vehicle fleet fuel efficiency. State\nagencies and other affected entities may substitute the use of 450\ngallons of 100\\% biodiesel (B100) for the acquisition of one AFV.\nAlternatively, using 2,250 gallons of biodiesel blends of 20\\% (B20) or\n9,000 gallons of biodiesel blends of 5\\% (B5) may also be substituted in\nplace of purchasing one AFV. No more than 50\\% of a given state agency\nfleet's AFV purchase requirement may be met by substituting B100, B20,\nor B5. (Reference Executive Order 111, 2001; Executive Order 142, 2005;\nand Executive Order 4, 2008)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     \\\\\n\t5 & 2001 & SC & State Agency Alternative Fuel Use Requirement                       & Whenever practical and economically feasible, all state agencies\noperating alternative fuel vehicles must use alternative fuels in those\nvehicles. Private businesses are encouraged to increase the use of\nalternative fuels in the state. (Reference Executive Order 2001-35)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           \\\\\n\t6 & 2002 & IL & Corn-to-Ethanol Research Pilot Plant                                & The Illinois Ethanol Research Advisory Board manages and operates\nthe National Corn-to-Ethanol Research Center (NCERC) Pilot Plant.\nThe NCERC Pilot Plant aims to reduce the cost of producing\nethanol through the development and commercialization of new\nproduction technologies, equipment, processes, feedstocks, and\nnew value added co- and by-products. The Illinois Ethanol\nResearch Advisory Board has six main responsibilities:\n\n* Review the annual operating plans and budget of the NCERC Pilot\nPlant;\n* Advise on research and development priorities and projects to\nbe carried out at the NCERC Pilot Plant;\n* Advise on policies and procedures regarding the management and\noperation of the NCERC Pilot Plant (including contracts, project\nselection, and personnel issues);\n* Develop by-laws;\n* Submit a final report to the governor and general assembly\noutlining progress, accomplishments, and a financial report for\nthe year; and\n* Establish and operate the NCERC at Southern Illinois University\nat Edwardsville as a State Biorefining Center of Excellence with\na focus on areas including the following: performing\ncollaborative research; offering training and educational\nservices; advancing the state biofuels industry; pursuing funding\nsources; and serving as an independent source for testing and\nvalidation.\n\nFor more information, see the NCERC ( http://www.ethanolresearch.com/ ) website.\n\n(Reference 110 Illinois Compiled Statutes ( http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/ilcs.asp ) 520/6.5 to\n520/6.6)\\\\\n\\end{tabular}\n","text/markdown":"\nA data.frame: 6 × 4\n\n| <!--/--> | Enacted.Year &lt;dbl&gt; | State &lt;chr&gt; | Title &lt;chr&gt; | Text &lt;chr&gt; |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| 1 | 1996 | MA | State Agency Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirement | State fleets must acquire AFVs according to the requirements of the\nEnergy Policy Act (EPAct) of 1992 and the Massachusetts Office of\nVehicle Management (OVM) must approve any light-duty vehicle\nacquisition. All agencies must purchase the most economical,\nfuel-efficient, and low emission vehicles appropriate to their mission.\nOVM, in collaboration with the Massachusetts Department of Energy\nResources, will set new minimum standards for vehicle mileage and work\nwith agencies to acquire vehicles that provide the best value for the\nCommonwealth on a total cost of ownership basis. (Reference Executive\nOrder 388, 1996, and Massachusetts Executive Office of Administration\nand Finance Administrative Bulletin 10, 2010)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                    |\n| 2 | 2000 | IA | State Fleet Biofuels Use and Fuel Efficiency                        | As part of the Green Government Initiative, the Iowa Office of Energy\nIndependence (OEI), Department of Administrative Services, Department of\nNatural Resources, and Department of Transportation lead a Biofuels Task\nForce. This group focuses on issues including increasing each state\nagency's use of biofuels to the maximum amount feasible and increasing\nthe fuel efficiency of the state's vehicle fleet. The Biofuels Task\nForce sets specific five- and ten-year targets related to these areas,\nwhich are included in the Green Government Master Plan. Progress toward\nthese goals will be tracked using a reporting system developed under the\nGreen Government Initiative, and resulting data will be made public via\nthe OEI whenever possible. (Reference Executive Order 6, 2008)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                               |\n| 3 | 2001 | MD | Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirements             | Maryland established an AFV goal under the plan for \\'Sustaining\nMaryland\\'s Future with Clean Power, Green Buildings and Energy\nEfficiency.\\' The state will revise fleet policy and purchasing\nguidelines to offer more flexibility in purchasing, where practical, low\nemission vehicles and AFVs for its fleet. The state must ensure that an\naverage of 50% of the fuel used to operate bi-fuel and flexible fuel\nvehicles are alternative fuel. The state must also help develop the\nrefueling and maintenance infrastructure required to make using certain\ntypes of AFV use practical. The state may provide technical assistance\nand other incentives to use clean technology, where practical, in state\ntransit fleets. (Reference [Executive\nOrder](https://governor.maryland.gov/category/executive-orders/)\n01.01.2001.02)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                        |\n| 4 | 2001 | NY | Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirements             | All new light-duty vehicles that state agencies and other affected\nentities procure must be AFVs, with the exception of designated\nspecialty, police, or emergency vehicles. Hybrid electric vehicles\nqualify under these requirements. State agencies and other affected\nentities that operate medium- and heavy-duty vehicles must implement\nstrategies to reduce petroleum consumption and emissions by using\nalternative fuels and improving vehicle fleet fuel efficiency. State\nagencies and other affected entities may substitute the use of 450\ngallons of 100% biodiesel (B100) for the acquisition of one AFV.\nAlternatively, using 2,250 gallons of biodiesel blends of 20% (B20) or\n9,000 gallons of biodiesel blends of 5% (B5) may also be substituted in\nplace of purchasing one AFV. No more than 50% of a given state agency\nfleet's AFV purchase requirement may be met by substituting B100, B20,\nor B5. (Reference Executive Order 111, 2001; Executive Order 142, 2005;\nand Executive Order 4, 2008)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                      |\n| 5 | 2001 | SC | State Agency Alternative Fuel Use Requirement                       | Whenever practical and economically feasible, all state agencies\noperating alternative fuel vehicles must use alternative fuels in those\nvehicles. Private businesses are encouraged to increase the use of\nalternative fuels in the state. (Reference Executive Order 2001-35)\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                            |\n| 6 | 2002 | IL | Corn-to-Ethanol Research Pilot Plant                                | The Illinois Ethanol Research Advisory Board manages and operates\nthe National Corn-to-Ethanol Research Center (NCERC) Pilot Plant.\nThe NCERC Pilot Plant aims to reduce the cost of producing\nethanol through the development and commercialization of new\nproduction technologies, equipment, processes, feedstocks, and\nnew value added co- and by-products. The Illinois Ethanol\nResearch Advisory Board has six main responsibilities:\n\n* Review the annual operating plans and budget of the NCERC Pilot\nPlant;\n* Advise on research and development priorities and projects to\nbe carried out at the NCERC Pilot Plant;\n* Advise on policies and procedures regarding the management and\noperation of the NCERC Pilot Plant (including contracts, project\nselection, and personnel issues);\n* Develop by-laws;\n* Submit a final report to the governor and general assembly\noutlining progress, accomplishments, and a financial report for\nthe year; and\n* Establish and operate the NCERC at Southern Illinois University\nat Edwardsville as a State Biorefining Center of Excellence with\na focus on areas including the following: performing\ncollaborative research; offering training and educational\nservices; advancing the state biofuels industry; pursuing funding\nsources; and serving as an independent source for testing and\nvalidation.\n\nFor more information, see the NCERC ( http://www.ethanolresearch.com/ ) website.\n\n(Reference 110 Illinois Compiled Statutes ( http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/ilcs.asp ) 520/6.5 to\n520/6.6) |\n\n","text/plain":"  Enacted.Year State\n1 1996         MA   \n2 2000         IA   \n3 2001         MD   \n4 2001         NY   \n5 2001         SC   \n6 2002         IL   \n  Title                                                              \n1 State Agency Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirement\n2 State Fleet Biofuels Use and Fuel Efficiency                       \n3 Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirements            \n4 Alternative Fuel Vehicle (AFV) Acquisition Requirements            \n5 State Agency Alternative Fuel Use Requirement                      \n6 Corn-to-Ethanol Research Pilot Plant                               \n  Text                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           \n1 State fleets must acquire AFVs according to the requirements of the\\nEnergy Policy Act (EPAct) of 1992 and the Massachusetts Office of\\nVehicle Management (OVM) must approve any light-duty vehicle\\nacquisition. All agencies must purchase the most economical,\\nfuel-efficient, and low emission vehicles appropriate to their mission.\\nOVM, in collaboration with the Massachusetts Department of Energy\\nResources, will set new minimum standards for vehicle mileage and work\\nwith agencies to acquire vehicles that provide the best value for the\\nCommonwealth on a total cost of ownership basis. (Reference Executive\\nOrder 388, 1996, and Massachusetts Executive Office of Administration\\nand Finance Administrative Bulletin 10, 2010)\\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                   \n2 As part of the Green Government Initiative, the Iowa Office of Energy\\nIndependence (OEI), Department of Administrative Services, Department of\\nNatural Resources, and Department of Transportation lead a Biofuels Task\\nForce. This group focuses on issues including increasing each state\\nagency's use of biofuels to the maximum amount feasible and increasing\\nthe fuel efficiency of the state's vehicle fleet. The Biofuels Task\\nForce sets specific five- and ten-year targets related to these areas,\\nwhich are included in the Green Government Master Plan. Progress toward\\nthese goals will be tracked using a reporting system developed under the\\nGreen Government Initiative, and resulting data will be made public via\\nthe OEI whenever possible. (Reference Executive Order 6, 2008)\\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                              \n3 Maryland established an AFV goal under the plan for \\\\'Sustaining\\nMaryland\\\\'s Future with Clean Power, Green Buildings and Energy\\nEfficiency.\\\\' The state will revise fleet policy and purchasing\\nguidelines to offer more flexibility in purchasing, where practical, low\\nemission vehicles and AFVs for its fleet. The state must ensure that an\\naverage of 50% of the fuel used to operate bi-fuel and flexible fuel\\nvehicles are alternative fuel. The state must also help develop the\\nrefueling and maintenance infrastructure required to make using certain\\ntypes of AFV use practical. The state may provide technical assistance\\nand other incentives to use clean technology, where practical, in state\\ntransit fleets. (Reference [Executive\\nOrder](https://governor.maryland.gov/category/executive-orders/)\\n01.01.2001.02)\\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       \n4 All new light-duty vehicles that state agencies and other affected\\nentities procure must be AFVs, with the exception of designated\\nspecialty, police, or emergency vehicles. Hybrid electric vehicles\\nqualify under these requirements. State agencies and other affected\\nentities that operate medium- and heavy-duty vehicles must implement\\nstrategies to reduce petroleum consumption and emissions by using\\nalternative fuels and improving vehicle fleet fuel efficiency. State\\nagencies and other affected entities may substitute the use of 450\\ngallons of 100% biodiesel (B100) for the acquisition of one AFV.\\nAlternatively, using 2,250 gallons of biodiesel blends of 20% (B20) or\\n9,000 gallons of biodiesel blends of 5% (B5) may also be substituted in\\nplace of purchasing one AFV. No more than 50% of a given state agency\\nfleet's AFV purchase requirement may be met by substituting B100, B20,\\nor B5. (Reference Executive Order 111, 2001; Executive Order 142, 2005;\\nand Executive Order 4, 2008)\\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     \n5 Whenever practical and economically feasible, all state agencies\\noperating alternative fuel vehicles must use alternative fuels in those\\nvehicles. Private businesses are encouraged to increase the use of\\nalternative fuels in the state. (Reference Executive Order 2001-35)\\n                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           \n6 The Illinois Ethanol Research Advisory Board manages and operates\\nthe National Corn-to-Ethanol Research Center (NCERC) Pilot Plant.\\nThe NCERC Pilot Plant aims to reduce the cost of producing\\nethanol through the development and commercialization of new\\nproduction technologies, equipment, processes, feedstocks, and\\nnew value added co- and by-products. The Illinois Ethanol\\nResearch Advisory Board has six main responsibilities:\\n\\n* Review the annual operating plans and budget of the NCERC Pilot\\nPlant;\\n* Advise on research and development priorities and projects to\\nbe carried out at the NCERC Pilot Plant;\\n* Advise on policies and procedures regarding the management and\\noperation of the NCERC Pilot Plant (including contracts, project\\nselection, and personnel issues);\\n* Develop by-laws;\\n* Submit a final report to the governor and general assembly\\noutlining progress, accomplishments, and a financial report for\\nthe year; and\\n* Establish and operate the NCERC at Southern Illinois University\\nat Edwardsville as a State Biorefining Center of Excellence with\\na focus on areas including the following: performing\\ncollaborative research; offering training and educational\\nservices; advancing the state biofuels industry; pursuing funding\\nsources; and serving as an independent source for testing and\\nvalidation.\\n\\nFor more information, see the NCERC ( http://www.ethanolresearch.com/ ) website.\\n\\n(Reference 110 Illinois Compiled Statutes ( http://www.ilga.gov/legislation/ilcs/ilcs.asp ) 520/6.5 to\\n520/6.6)"}}},"pos":7,"scrolled":true,"start":1772991190022,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991193280,"exec_count":88,"id":"d3fcf6","input":"#look for missing data\ntable(clean_state_acts$State)\ntable(clean_state_acts$Enacted.Year) #missing years 1997 - 1999","kernel":"ir","last":31,"output":{"0":{"data":{"text/plain":"\nAK AL AR AZ CA CO CT DE FL GA HI IA ID IL IN KS KY LA MA MD ME MI MN MO MS MT \n 3  4  3  8 15 10  2  2  8  1  8  3  3 17  4  1  5  9  9  4  6  7  9  1  3  3 \nNC ND NE NH NJ NM NV NY OH OK OR PA RI SC SD TN TX UT VA VT WA WI WV WY \n 3  1  3  8  6  7  6  7  2 10 10  2  5  2  6  3  3  9  7 12 11  8  2  5 "}},"1":{"data":{"text/plain":"\n1996 2000 2001 2002 2003 2004 2005 2006 2007 2008 2009 2010 2011 2012 2013 2014 \n   1    1    3    1    1    5    6   12   30   23   37   19   20   19   16    9 \n2015 2016 2017 2018 2019 2020 2021 2022 \n  13    4   26   13   15    1    2    9 "}}},"pos":8,"start":1772991193235,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991195647,"exec_count":89,"id":"b32d05","input":"#group by year and state to find missing data for each state\n\nstate_stats <- clean_state_acts %>%\n    \n    #find total acts per state per year\n    group_by(Enacted.Year, State) %>%\n        mutate(Acts = n()) %>% #counts number of enacted laws each year\n        distinct() %>%\n\n        dplyr::select(State, Enacted.Year, Acts) %>%\n        arrange (State, Enacted.Year) %>%\n        distinct() %>% #there are missing years for each state\n        \n    #group by State make sure they all have data for years 1996 - 2022\n    group_by(State) %>%\n        complete(Enacted.Year = 1996:2022, fill = list(n = 0)) %>% #filling in missing years for each state\n        mutate(Acts = replace_na(Acts, 0)) %>% #put number of acts with zerso for each missing year\n        ungroup()\n    \nhead(state_stats)","kernel":"ir","last":593,"output":{"0":{"data":{"iframe":"88886d777848447ab6d94c7d061f526d9aee04ac","text/latex":"A tibble: 6 × 3\n\\begin{tabular}{lll}\n State & Enacted.Year & Acts\\\\\n <chr> & <dbl> & <int>\\\\\n\\hline\n\t AK & 1996 & 0\\\\\n\t AK & 1997 & 0\\\\\n\t AK & 1998 & 0\\\\\n\t AK & 1999 & 0\\\\\n\t AK & 2000 & 0\\\\\n\t AK & 2001 & 0\\\\\n\\end{tabular}\n","text/markdown":"\nA tibble: 6 × 3\n\n| State &lt;chr&gt; | Enacted.Year &lt;dbl&gt; | Acts &lt;int&gt; |\n|---|---|---|\n| AK | 1996 | 0 |\n| AK | 1997 | 0 |\n| AK | 1998 | 0 |\n| AK | 1999 | 0 |\n| AK | 2000 | 0 |\n| AK | 2001 | 0 |\n\n","text/plain":"  State Enacted.Year Acts\n1 AK    1996         0   \n2 AK    1997         0   \n3 AK    1998         0   \n4 AK    1999         0   \n5 AK    2000         0   \n6 AK    2001         0   "}}},"pos":9,"start":1772991195160,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991197954,"exec_count":90,"id":"5dc58d","input":"#find total number of enacted state laws per year\n\nyear_state_stats <- state_stats %>%\n  group_by(Enacted.Year) %>%\n      summarize(Total_Acts = sum(Acts, na.rm = TRUE)) %>% \n      arrange(Enacted.Year) %>%\n      ungroup() #for graphing\n\nhead(year_state_stats)","kernel":"ir","last":159,"output":{"0":{"data":{"iframe":"4b2a2e2bc0685a827538dcfecc7e57bec07e164b","text/latex":"A tibble: 6 × 2\n\\begin{tabular}{ll}\n Enacted.Year & Total\\_Acts\\\\\n <dbl> & <int>\\\\\n\\hline\n\t 1996 & 1\\\\\n\t 1997 & 0\\\\\n\t 1998 & 0\\\\\n\t 1999 & 0\\\\\n\t 2000 & 1\\\\\n\t 2001 & 3\\\\\n\\end{tabular}\n","text/markdown":"\nA tibble: 6 × 2\n\n| Enacted.Year &lt;dbl&gt; | Total_Acts &lt;int&gt; |\n|---|---|\n| 1996 | 1 |\n| 1997 | 0 |\n| 1998 | 0 |\n| 1999 | 0 |\n| 2000 | 1 |\n| 2001 | 3 |\n\n","text/plain":"  Enacted.Year Total_Acts\n1 1996         1         \n2 1997         0         \n3 1998         0         \n4 1999         0         \n5 2000         1         \n6 2001         3         "}}},"pos":10,"start":1772991197863,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991200597,"exec_count":91,"id":"a4ef07","input":"#Look at distribution of number of enacted laws\nhist(state_stats$Acts) #enacted laws per state\n\nhist(year_state_stats$Total_Acts) #total enacted laws across US states","kernel":"ir","last":535,"output":{"0":{"data":{"image/png":"1dec44dc7100ded435aa25e7b4a0d4c2743ae4d6","text/plain":"Plot with title “Histogram of state_stats$Acts”"},"metadata":{"image/png":{"height":900,"width":1200}}},"1":{"data":{"image/png":"c7cffa85e00e673981d3392239aa840ea241a39a","text/plain":"Plot with title “Histogram of year_state_stats$Total_Acts”"},"metadata":{"image/png":{"height":900,"width":1200}}}},"pos":12,"start":1772991200110,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991205310,"exec_count":92,"id":"f187e9","input":"#trend analysis - plot each dataset on top of each other\noptions(repr.plot.width = 20, repr.plot.height = 8)\n\nstate_trendline <- ggplot() + \n    geom_line(data = state_stats, aes(x = Enacted.Year, y = Acts, group = State, color = State), alpha = 0.5, size = 1) + #totals per state\n    \n    #create second color scale for the geom_segments\n    new_scale_color() +\n    scale_color_manual(name = \"Federal Law\", \n                     values = \"red\") +\n\n    ##################### add in federal acts ################\n\n    #2005 - Energy Policy Act\n    geom_segment(aes(x = 2005, xend = 2005, y = 0, yend = 6, color = \"Federal Law\"),\n                linetype = \"dashed\", size = 1) + #vertical line cut below top of graph\n    annotate(\"text\", x = 2004, y = 6.25, \n             label = \"US Energy Policy Act\", \n             vjust = 0, color = \"black\", size = 6) + #text\n\n    #2008\n        #Food, Conservation, and Energy Act\n        #Energy Improvement and Extension Act\n    geom_segment(aes(x = 2008, xend = 2008, y = 0, yend = 6, color = \"Federal Law\"),\n                linetype = \"dashed\", size = 1) + #vertical line cut below top of graph\n    annotate(\"text\", x = 2010, y = 6.25, \n              label = \"US Food, Conservation, and Energy Act \\n& Energy Improvement and Extension Act\",\n              vjust = 0, color = \"black\", size = 6) + #text\n\n    #2016 - Consolidated Appropriations Act\n    geom_segment(aes(x = 2016, xend = 2016, y = 0, yend = 6, color = \"Federal Law\"),\n                linetype = \"dashed\", size = 1) + #vertical line cut below top of graph\n    annotate(\"text\", x = 2018, y = 6.25, \n             label = \"US Consolidated Appropriations Act\", \n             vjust = 0, color = \"black\", size = 6) + #text\n\n    scale_y_continuous(expand = expansion(mult = c(0.05, 0.15))) + \n\n    ########################################################\n\n    #labels\n    labs(title = \"Enacted United States Fuel Energy Laws and Regulations by State\", \n             subtitle = \"Data Source: US Department of Energy - Alternative Fuels Data Center\", \n             x = \"Enacted Year\",\n             y = \"Number of State Laws and Regulations\") +\n\n    theme_bw() +\n    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 30, face = \"bold\"), # Adjust text sizes\n          plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 20, face = \"bold.italic\"),\n          axis.title = element_text(size = 20)\n         ) \n\nstate_trendline","kernel":"ir","last":309,"output":{"0":{"data":{"image/png":"7a94e45d4ec968b29216853eab96534906224ea8","text/plain":"plot without title"},"metadata":{"image/png":{"height":480,"width":1200}}}},"pos":13,"start":1772991204263,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991223552,"exec_count":93,"id":"a68cda","input":"options(repr.plot.width = 20, repr.plot.height = 8)\nUS_trendline <- ggplot() + \n\n      #manual legend\n      scale_color_manual(name = c(\"Annual Trendine, Federal Law\"), #legend name\n                         values = c(\"black\", \"red\")) +    #color\n\n    geom_line(data = year_state_stats, aes(x = Enacted.Year, y = Total_Acts, group = 1,  color = \"Annual Trendine\"), size = 1) + #US state total\n\n    #add in US federal policy dates\n    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 2005, color = \"Federal Law\"), linetype = \"dashed\", size = 1) +\n    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 2008, color = \"Federal Law\"), linetype = \"dashed\", size = 1) +\n    geom_vline(aes(xintercept = 2016, color = \"Federal Law\"), linetype = \"dashed\", size = 1) +\n\n    #labels\n    labs(title = \"Total Enacted State Fuel Energy Laws and Regulations in the United States\",  \n             subtitle = \"Data Source: US Department of Energy - Alternative Fuels Data Center\", \n             x = \"Enacted Year\",\n             y = \"Total Number of State Laws and Regulations\") +\n    \n    theme_bw() +\n    theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 30, face = \"bold\"), # Adjust text sizes\n          plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 20, face = \"bold.italic\"),\n          axis.title = element_text(size = 20)\n         ) \n\n\nUS_trendline","kernel":"ir","last":587,"output":{"0":{"data":{"image/png":"f037a3a5d76570fb8254f4f4ffa900a4a31101c1","text/plain":"plot without title"},"metadata":{"image/png":{"height":480,"width":1200}}}},"pos":14,"start":1772991222923,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
{"cell_type":"code","end":1772991227873,"exec_count":94,"id":"2716b0","input":"#combine graphs vertically\noptions(repr.plot.width = 20, repr.plot.height = 15)\ncombined_trends <- state_trendline / US_trendline\ncombined_trends","kernel":"ir","last":1361,"output":{"0":{"data":{"image/png":"f6c7afa9fc3bf4fd73e933556b23db768b8fd4b6","text/plain":"plot without title"},"metadata":{"image/png":{"height":900,"width":1200}}}},"pos":15,"start":1772991226604,"state":"done","type":"cell"}
